Quick getting‑started checklist
- Pick the right product for you: Copilot in IDE (VS Code, JetBrains, Visual Studio, Neovim, etc.), Copilot Chat, or Copilot for CLI.  
- Install the Copilot extension/plugin for your editor and sign in with your GitHub account.  
- Open a repository or a new file and enable inline suggestions (the extension usually prompts).  
- Try this simple workflow: write a descriptive comment or function signature, wait for a suggestion, accept with the editor’s accept key (Tab/Right Arrow or the editor command), then review and tweak.  
- Keep suggestions small at first: generate a single function, then write unit tests for it. Repeat with refactors and documentation generation.

Practical first exercises (15–30 minutes each)
- “Create a function”: write a comment describing a small utility (e.g., "Return the top 3 most frequent words from text") and accept or cycle suggestions.  
- “Write tests”: ask Copilot to generate unit tests for the function it produced, run them, fix failures.  
- “Refactor”: select a messy function and ask Copilot to refactor it for readability or performance.  
- “Explain code”: paste a tricky block and ask Copilot to explain it in plain English or produce inline documentation.  
- “Convert languages”: give a small function and ask Copilot to translate it to another language.

Tips for better results
- Be explicit in your comments/prompts (inputs, edge cases, expected return types).  
- Use stepwise prompts: ask for the function first, then tests, then documentation.  
- Cycle suggestions (Ctrl/Cmd+Enter or the extension UI) if the first suggestion isn’t right.  
- Inspect generated code carefully — treat suggestions as a starting point, not final production code.  
- Don’t paste secrets (API keys, passwords) into prompts or files; remove sensitive data from examples.

Configuration & workflow suggestions
- Configure acceptance keys and suggestion behavior in the extension settings to match your workflow.  
- Use Copilot to scaffold code and tests, but run linters/formatters and your CI locally.  
- For pair‑programming style work, try Copilot Chat (if available in your plan) for back-and-forth reasoning.

Safety, licensing, and privacy
- Review generated code for license compatibility and security issues before merging.  
- Avoid submitting proprietary or confidential code as prompts.  
- Check your organization’s Copilot policy if you’re using Copilot at work.

